{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492859"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1171"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1171"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.08,0.34,0.08,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1171"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51781"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1171"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1171"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"},{"type":"tags","id":"1198"},{"type":"tags","id":"2418"},{"type":"tags","id":"3424"},{"type":"tags","id":"9166"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35991"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51781"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents with a six month history of heartburn and regurgitation. He is able to eat a normal, varied diet without any problems. He is a non-smoker, walks 2km every day and goes to the gym regularly. He has not had any major illnesses in the past and does not use any medications. His physical examination is unremarkable. A barium swallow is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Esomeprazole","Nifedipine","Oesophageal dilatation","Laparoscopic cardiomyotomy","Laparoscopic fundoplication"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe barium swallow shows a small hiatus hernia with volume reflux, consistent with gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD). There is no evidence of stricture formation. The narrowed area is the cardia. The most appropriate initial management for this patient is acid suppression with a proton pump inhibitor (eg \u003Cstrong\u003Eesomeprazole\u003C/strong\u003E). The large majority of patients with GORD get good control of their symptoms with a proton pump inhibitor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal dilatation\u003C/strong\u003E is only needed if stricture is present. The patient does not have any dysphagia, so there is no clinical nor radiological evidence of stricture formation. With the advent of effective acid suppression (proton pump inhibitors), stricture formation is now a relatively uncommon complication of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFundoplication\u003C/strong\u003E is last line therapy for uncontrolled GORD and considering no treatment has been trialled so far, this approach would be inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium channel blockers (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Enifedipine\u003C/strong\u003E) and \u003Cstrong\u003Elaproscopic cardiomyotomy\u003C/strong\u003E are management options for achalasia. The barium swallow is not consistent with this diagnosis (tapering of the inferior oesophagus is seen with achalasia).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A proton pump inhibitor provides good symptomatic relief for most patients with uncomplicated gastro-oesophageal reflux disease."],"references":["Fass R. Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease. N Engl J Med 2022; 387:1207-16. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36170502/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1171"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18342"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20993"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18342"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/df759cc1-6102-4651-b340-ca22efac0d04.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/df759cc1-6102-4651-b340-ca22efac0d04.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":472,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20993"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mA5BJDchQ7Dkg44nxk0MPBnIrLvqAr.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/mA5BJDchQ7Dkg44nxk0MPBnIrLvqAr.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":472,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37081"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-28T22:02:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-14T08:45:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1171"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51781"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","lin